<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="e85f1c1b-6fca-5df5-8ed1-3aae84060a22" activityNameId="a30bf2d1-3837-4bdd-85b8-b0ed65d03524" parentActivityId="47af2865-97fd-4922-966a-91d466a675dd" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">acrylic acid production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">79-10-7</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Acroleic acid</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">2-Propenoic acid</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Propene acid</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Propenoic acid</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends with the production of 1 kg of acrylic acid. The dataset includes the processing of the raw materials and chemicals used for production, as well as emissions to air and water.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of liquid acrylic acid. Acrylic acid is a colourless, slightly water soluble liquid with an acrid odour. It belongs to the carboxylic acids. The acid may be transported stabilised with inhibitors (such as hydroquinone derivatives) to prevent polymerisation. The chemical and physical properties of the polymers can be modified through controlled variation in the selection and balance of the monomers, the extent of cross-linking and molecular mass. This flexibility is complemented by high resistance to chemical and environmental degradation, strength, clarity, and being readily available in high purity forms (Ohara et al. 2011).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Acrylic acid is a versatile chemical that can be esterified, aminated or otherwise modified and polymerised to complex molecular arrangements to suit requirements. This characteristic enables a broad range of reactions for providing performance characteristics to a range of polymers. The esters are produced by reacting acrylic acid with alcohols especially ethanol, methanol and butanol that may be saponified, converted to other esters or amides by aminolysis. Acrylates are derivatives of acrylic acid (such as methyl and ethyl acrylate) whose properties have been sufficiently modified to enable of acrylic acid to be used in different media as emulsion and solution polymers. As emulsions, these products may be used as coatings, finishes and binders leading to applications in paints, adhesives, and polishes with solutions used for industrial coatings. Two-third of the world's production of acrylic acid is used to produce acrylic esters (acrylates) primarily for use in emulsions and solution polymers for latex-based paints, coatings, adhesives and textiles. Polymers of acrylic acid can be produced as superabsorbent materials (e.g. for dipers), and soluble as a replacement for phosphates in detergents. Both of these represent fast growing applications for acrylic acid. The chemical and physical properties of the polymers can be modified through controlled variation in the selection and balance of the monomers, the extent of cross-linking and molecular mass. This flexibility is complemented by high resistance to chemical and environmental degradation, strength, clarity, and being readily available in high purity forms.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Acrylic acid is produced mainly by the oxidation of propylene, using either a single-step or two-step process. This dataset models the production of acrylic acid using the two-step propylene oxidation process. The data is mainly based on pubications about the theoretical production of acrylic acid.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">In this dataset, the raw material inputs, and process-specific material exchanges, are modelled with a generic stoichiometry-based tool, using literature or estimated yields. The emissions are modelled with a default value, which is estimated  based on losses, unreacted chemicals, among others. At the same time, the energy consumption is based on data from literature sources.  Finally, the auxiliary (i.e., cooling water and infrastructure) exchanges are modelled with a default value based on industry data from literature sources.   For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Ohara, T., Sato, T., Shimizu, N., Prescher, G., Schwind, H., Weiberg, O., Marten, K. and Greim, H. 2011. Acrylic Acid and Derivatives. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled at the Global level. The main material inputs and outputs of this activity are generated with on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields.  Furthermore, the source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dataset could also be considered as not geography-specific, and thus, valid for a broader geographical coverage.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989)</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Most of the commercial acrylic acid is manufactured by the oxidation of propylene.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Two production processes can be distiguished:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">- Single-step propylene oxidation: The yield in the single-step process is at best approximately 50-60%. Another drawback is the limited lifetime of the catalyst, which is a multicomponent system composed of polyvalent oxides with molybdenum oxide as main component and tellurium oxide as promotor. The disadvantages of this process lead to the development of the two-step process.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">CH2=CHCH3 (propylene) + 3/2 O2 → CH2=CHCO2H (acrylic acid) + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">- Two-step propylene oxidation: The limited life of the catalyst has promoted a two stage manufacturing process via acrolein using two catalysts. The first stage is the oxidation of propylene to acrolein using a bismuth molybdate catalyst in a strongly exothermic reaction (at about 370°C). In the second stage, the acrolein gas is passed over a molybdenum vanadium oxide catalyst that is also exothermic (at about 270°C - about 100°C cooler than the first stage). The crude acrylic acid is then cooled to about 80°C, absorbed in water (30 to 60% concentration) and extracted with organic solvent or water (depending on the concentration).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">CH2=CHCH3 (propylene) + O2 → CH2=CHCHO (acrolein) + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">CH2=CHCHO + 1/2 O2 → CH2=CHCO2H (acrylic acid)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">In a subsequent step, acrylic acid is separated from the large volume of water present in the absorber effluent. This purification runs either by distillation from the solvent or by removing from water with added inhibitors to minimise the formation of polymers. Conversion rates of almost 100% conversion for acrolein and yields of acrylic acid greater than 90 % are achievable at commercial scales of production depending on technology, catalysts and conditions.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">The inventory in this dataset models the production of acrylic acid from propylene by the two-step oxidation process, based on the amount of output products obtained from the literature and the consideration of the complete scheme of competing reactions. Namely, an overall yield of 95% was assumed for the reaction scheme that produces acrylic acid based on the two stage process. At the same time, a yield of 95% was assumed for any additional side reaction that produces acetic acid as byproduct.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Ohara, T., Sato, T., Shimizu, N., Prescher, G., Schwind, H., Weiberg, O., Marten, K. and Greim, H. 2011. Acrylic Acid and Derivatives. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989)</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="1989-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The time period spans from the earliest year from which at least one of the input values was obtained until 2022, but overall form the most realistic picture of the production. Besides, the activity is partly generated, in terms of material inputs and outputs, based on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields, which does not expect to change over time.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data (from 1989) for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park. The values are a 5-year average of data from 2015 to 2019 published by the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. The end time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure and in the comments of the exchanges.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989)</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
